	abstract = {In this paper, an all-solid-state nitrate doped polypyrrole (PPy(NO(3)(-)) ion-selective electrode (ISE) was prepared with a nanohybrid composite film of  gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) and electrochemically reduced graphene oxide (ERGO).  Preliminary tests on the ISE based in-situ soil nitrate-nitrogen (NO(3)(-)-N)  monitoring was conducted in a laboratory 3-stage column. Comparisons were made  between the NO(3)(-)-N content of in-situ soil percolate solution and  laboratory-prepared extract solution. Possible influential factors of sample  depth, NO(3)(-)-N content, soil texture, and moisture were varied. Field-emission  scanning electron microscopy (FESEM) and X-ray powder diffraction (XRD)  characterized morphology and content information of the composite film of  ERGO/AuNPs. Due to the performance excellence for conductivity, stability, and  hydrophobicity, the ISE with ERGO/AuNPs illustrates an acceptable detection range  from 10(-1) to 10(-5) M. The response time was determined to be about 10 s. The  lifetime was 65 days, which revealed great potential for the implementation of  the ERGO/AuNPs mediated ISE for in-situ NO(3)(-)-N monitoring. In-situ NO(3)(-)-N  testing results conducted by the all-solid-state ISE followed a similar trend  with the standard UV-VIS method.},
